(7, 11, '0004_FIRM_FOUNDATIONS.txt', '**Title: Navigating Wall Street: Foundations, Illusions, and a Random Walk**', '**Title: Navigating Wall Street: Foundations, Illusions, and a Random Walk**\n**Text:**\nWhat is a cynic? A man who knows the price of everything and the value of nothing.\nOscar Wilde, *Lady Windermere\'s Fan*\nIn this book, I will take you on a random walk down Wall Street, providing a guided tour of the complex world of finance and offering practical advice on investment opportunities and strategies. Many people believe that individual investors have little chance against Wall Street professionals, citing sophisticated investment strategies using complex derivatives and high-frequency trading. They read news reports of accounting fraud, massive takeovers, and the activities of well-financed hedge funds. This complexity suggests that there is no place for the individual investor in today’s markets. Nothing could be further from the truth. You can perform as well as the experts, perhaps even better. It was the steady investors who kept their composure when the stock market plummeted in March 2009 and subsequently saw the value of their holdings recover and generate attractive returns. Conversely, many professionals lost heavily in 2008 by investing in derivative securities they didn\'t understand, and during the early 2000s by overloading their portfolios with overpriced tech stocks.\nThis book is a concise guide for the individual investor, covering topics ranging from insurance to income taxes. It explains how to buy life insurance and how to avoid being exploited by banks and brokers. It even addresses investments in gold and diamonds. However, its primary focus is on common stocks, an investment medium that has historically provided generous long-term returns and continues to offer promising opportunities. The life-cycle investment guide in Part Four provides specific portfolio recommendations for individuals of all age groups to meet their financial goals, including advice on retirement investing.\nWHAT IS A RANDOM WALK?\nA random walk is a process where future steps or directions cannot be predicted based on past history. When applied to the stock market, it implies that short-term changes in stock prices are unpredictable. Investment advisory services, earnings forecasts, and intricate chart patterns are rendered useless. On Wall Street, the term \"random walk\" is often considered an insult, an epithet coined by academics and hurled at professional forecasters. Taken to its logical conclusion, it suggests that a blindfolded monkey throwing darts at stock listings could select a portfolio as effectively as an expert.\nFinancial analysts in pinstripe suits naturally dislike being compared to primates. They retort that academics are so engrossed in equations and Greek symbols (not to mention convoluted prose) that they couldn\'t distinguish a bull market from a bear market, even in a china shop. Market professionals defend themselves against the academic onslaught with two techniques: fundamental analysis and technical analysis, which we will examine in Part Two. Academics counter these tactics by complicating the random-walk theory with three versions (weak, semi-strong, and strong) and by developing their own theory, the \"new investment technology.\" This includes the concept of \"beta,\" including \"smart beta,\" which I intend to critique. By the early 2000s, some academics had even joined professionals in arguing that the stock market was at least somewhat predictable. As you can see, a significant battle is underway, fought with serious intent because the stakes are tenure for academics and bonuses for professionals. That\'s why I believe you\'ll find this random walk down Wall Street engaging. It contains all the elements of high drama, including fortunes made and lost, and classic arguments about their causes.\nBefore we begin, allow me to introduce myself and outline my qualifications as your guide. My background provides three distinct perspectives on the stock market, which I have drawn upon in writing this book. First, I offer my professional experience in investment analysis and portfolio management. I began my career as a market professional with a leading Wall Street investment firm. Later, I chaired the investment committee of a multinational insurance company and served for many years as a director of one of the world\'s largest investment companies. These experiences have been invaluable. Some things in life cannot be fully appreciated or understood without firsthand experience. The same could be said of the stock market.\nSecond, I draw on my current positions as an economist and chair of several investment committees. Specializing in securities markets and investment behavior, I have acquired detailed knowledge of academic research and new findings on investment opportunities.\nLast, but certainly not least, I have been a lifelong investor and a successful participant in the market. I won’t disclose how successful, as academics are not supposed to make money. A professor may inherit, marry, and spend large sums, but earning a lot of money is considered unacademic. Teachers are expected to be dedicated, or so politicians and administrators often claim, especially when justifying low academic salaries. Academics should be seekers of knowledge, not financial reward. Therefore, I will share my victories on Wall Street in the former sense.\nThis book contains many facts and figures, but don\'t be intimidated. It is specifically designed for the financial layperson and offers practical, tested investment advice. No prior knowledge is required. All you need is interest and a desire to have your investments work for you.\nINVESTING AS A WAY OF LIFE TODAY\nAt this point, it\'s important to define what I mean by \"investing\" and how I distinguish it from \"speculating.\" I view investing as purchasing assets to generate profit through reasonably predictable income (dividends, interest, or rentals) and/or long-term appreciation. The timeframe for investment returns and the predictability of those returns are the key factors that differentiate investing from speculating. A speculator buys stocks hoping for short-term gains over days or weeks. An investor buys stocks likely to produce a dependable future stream of cash returns and capital gains over years or decades.\nLet me be clear: this is not a book for speculators. I won\'t promise overnight riches or stock-market miracles. A suitable subtitle for this book might be \"The Get Rich Slowly but Surely Book.\" Remember, your investments must generate a rate of return equal to inflation just to maintain your purchasing power.\nInflation in the United States and most of the developed world fell to 2 percent or below in the early 2000s, and some analysts believe that relative price stability will continue indefinitely. They argue that inflation is the exception rather than the rule and that historical periods of rapid technological progress and peacetime economies were periods of stable or even falling prices. While little or no inflation may occur in the coming decades, investors should not dismiss the possibility that inflation will accelerate again in the future. Although productivity growth accelerated in the 1990s and early 2000s, it has recently slowed, and history shows that the pace of improvement has always been uneven. Moreover, productivity improvements are more difficult to achieve in some service-oriented activities. It will still take four musicians to play a string quartet and one surgeon to perform an appendectomy throughout the twenty-first century. If musicians\' and surgeons\' salaries rise over time, so will the cost of concert tickets and appendectomies. Therefore, upward pressure on prices cannot be ignored.\nEven if inflation were to proceed at a rate of 2 to 3 percent, significantly lower than the rates of the 1970s and early 1980s, the effect on our purchasing power would still be significant. The table on the following page illustrates the impact of an average inflation rate of nearly 4 percent over the 1962-2014 period. My morning newspaper has increased in price by 4,900 percent. My afternoon Hershey bar is twenty times more expensive, and it\'s actually smaller than it was in 1962, when I was in graduate school. If inflation continued at the same rate, today\'s morning paper would cost more than four dollars by the year 2020. Clearly, to cope with even mild inflation, we must adopt investment strategies that maintain our real purchasing power; otherwise, we are destined for a steadily declining standard of living.\nInvesting requires effort, make no mistake. Romantic novels are filled with stories of great family fortunes lost through neglect or lack of financial knowledge. Who can forget the sound of the cherry orchard being cut down in Chekhov\'s play? Free enterprise, not the Marxist system, caused the downfall of the Ranevsky family: they failed to work to preserve their wealth. Even if you entrust your funds to an investment advisor or a mutual fund, you still need to determine which advisor or fund is most suitable to manage your money. The information in this book should make your investment decisions easier.\n1963 data.\nSource: For 1962 prices, Forbes, Nov. 1, 1977, and various government and private sources for 2014 prices.\nMost importantly, investing is enjoyable. It\'s rewarding to test your intellect against the vast investment community and to be rewarded with increased assets. It\'s exciting to review your investment returns and see them accumulate faster than your salary. It\'s also stimulating to learn about new ideas for products and services, and innovations in financial investments. A successful investor is typically a well-rounded individual who applies natural curiosity and intellectual interest to their investments.\nINVESTING IN THEORY\nAll investment returns, whether from common stocks or exceptional diamonds, depend to varying degrees on future events. This is what makes investing fascinating: it\'s a gamble where success hinges on the ability to predict the future. Traditionally, investment professionals have used one of two approaches to asset valuation: the firm-foundation theory or the castle-in-the-air theory. Millions of dollars have been made and lost based on these theories, which appear to be mutually exclusive. Understanding these two approaches is crucial for making sensible investment decisions and avoiding serious mistakes. Toward the end of the twentieth century, a third theory, originating in academia and called the \"new investment technology,\" gained popularity on Wall Street. I will describe this theory and its application to investment analysis later in the book.\nTHE FIRM-FOUNDATION THEORY\nThe firm-foundation theory asserts that every investment instrument, whether a common stock or a piece of real estate, has an intrinsic value that can be determined through careful analysis of current conditions and future prospects. When market prices fall below (or rise above) this intrinsic value, a buying (or selling) opportunity arises, as this discrepancy will eventually be corrected, according to the theory. Investing then becomes a straightforward process of comparing an asset\'s actual price with its intrinsic value.\nAttributing the origin of the firm-foundation theory to a single individual is difficult. S. Eliot Guild is often credited, but John B. Williams provided the classic development of the technique, particularly its nuances.\nIn *The Theory of Investment Value*, Williams presented a formula for determining a stock\'s intrinsic value, based on dividend income. To make things complicated, he introduced the concept of discounting. Discounting involves looking at income backwards. Instead of calculating how much money you will have next year (e.g., $1.05 if you put $1 in a savings certificate at 5 percent interest), you look at money expected in the future and calculate its current value (e.g., next year\'s $1 is worth approximately $0.95 today, which could be invested at 5 percent to produce approximately $1 at that time). Williams was serious about this, arguing that a stock\'s intrinsic value equals the present (or discounted) value of all its future dividends. Investors were advised to discount the value of money received later. Because few understood it, the term \"discounting\" became popular among investment professionals. Professor Irving Fisher of Yale, a distinguished economist and investor, further popularized it.\nThe logic of the firm-foundation theory is respectable and can be illustrated with common stocks. The theory emphasizes that a stock\'s value should be based on the stream of earnings a company will distribute in the future as dividends. The greater the present dividends and their rate of increase, the greater the stock\'s value. Thus, differences in growth rates are a major factor in stock valuation. However, future expectations introduce uncertainty. Security analysts must estimate not only long-term growth rates but also how long extraordinary growth can be sustained. When the market becomes overly enthusiastic about future growth, Wall Street commonly believes that stocks are discounting not only the future but also the afterlife. The point is that the firm-foundation theory relies on tricky forecasts of the extent and duration of future growth, making the foundation of intrinsic value less dependable than claimed.\nThe firm-foundation theory is not limited to economists. Benjamin Graham and David Dodd\'s influential book, *Security Analysis*, converted a generation of Wall Street security analysts to the approach. Sound investment management, the analysts learned, simply involved buying securities whose prices were temporarily below intrinsic value and selling those whose prices were temporarily too high. It was that easy. Instructions for determining intrinsic value were provided, and any competent analyst could calculate it with simple arithmetic. Perhaps the most successful disciple of the Graham and Dodd approach was Warren Buffett, often called the \"Sage of Omaha,\" who compiled a legendary investment record allegedly by following the firm-foundation theory.\nTHE CASTLE-IN-THE-AIR THEORY\nThe castle-in-the-air theory of investing focuses on psychological values. John Maynard Keynes, a famous economist and successful investor, articulated the theory most clearly in 1936. He believed that professional investors prefer to analyze how the crowd of investors is likely to behave in the future and how, during periods of optimism, they tend to build castles in the air. The successful investor tries to anticipate which investment situations are most susceptible to public castle-building and buys before the crowd.\nAccording to Keynes, the firm-foundation theory requires too much work and is of doubtful value. Keynes practiced what he preached. While London\'s financial men toiled in crowded offices, he played the market from his bed for half an hour each morning. This leisurely approach earned him millions for his account and increased the market value of his college\'s endowment, King\'s College, Cambridge, tenfold.\nDuring the Depression years when Keynes gained fame, most people focused on his ideas for stimulating the economy. It was difficult for anyone to build castles in the air or imagine that others would. Nevertheless, in his book *The General Theory of Employment, Interest and Money*, Keynes devoted a chapter to the stock market and the importance of investor expectations.\nRegarding stocks, Keynes noted that no one knows for sure what will influence future earnings prospects and dividend payments. As a result, he said, most people are primarily concerned not with making superior long-term forecasts of an investment\'s probable yield over its lifetime, but with foreseeing changes in the conventional basis of valuation shortly before the general public does. In other words, Keynes applied psychological principles rather than financial evaluation to the study of the stock market. He wrote, \"It is not sensible to pay 25 for an investment of which you believe the prospective yield to justify a value of 30, if you also believe that the market will value it at 20 three months hence.\"\nKeynes described playing the stock market in terms readily understandable by his fellow Englishmen: \"It is analogous to entering a newspaper beauty-judging contest in which one must select the six prettiest faces out of a hundred photographs, with the prize going to the person whose selections most nearly conform to those of the group as a whole.\"\nThe smart player recognizes that personal criteria of beauty are irrelevant in determining the contest winner. A better strategy is to select the faces other players are likely to fancy. This logic tends to snowball. After all, the other participants are likely to play the game with at least as keen a perception. Thus, the optimal strategy is not to pick the faces the player finds prettiest, or the faces other players are likely to fancy, but to predict what the average opinion is likely to be about what the average opinion will be, or to proceed even further along this sequence. So much for British beauty contests.\nThe newspaper-contest analogy represents the ultimate form of the castle-in-the-air theory of price determination. An investment is worth a certain price to a buyer because she expects to sell it to someone else at a higher price. In other words, the investment holds itself up by its own bootstraps. The new buyer, in turn, anticipates that future buyers will assign an even higher value.\nIn this kind of world, a sucker is born every minute and exists to buy your investments at a higher price than you paid. Any price will do as long as others are willing to pay more. There is no reason, only mass psychology. All the smart investor has to do is get in at the very beginning. This theory might less charitably be called the \"greater fool theory.\" It\'s perfectly acceptable to pay three times what something is worth as long as you can find someone to pay five times its worth later on.\nThe castle-in-the-air theory has many advocates in both the financial and academic communities. Nobel laureate Robert Shiller, in his book *Irrational Exuberance*, argues that the mania in Internet and high-tech stocks during the late 1990s can only be explained by mass psychology. During the early 2000s, \"behavioral theories\" of the stock market, emphasizing crowd psychology, gained favor at leading economics departments and business schools worldwide. Psychologist Daniel Kahneman won the Nobel Prize in Economics in 2002 for his contributions to behavioral finance. Oskar Morgenstern was a leading champion of the castle-in-the-air theory, arguing that the search for intrinsic value in stocks is futile. He believed that every investor should post the following Latin maxim above his desk:\n*Res tantum valet quantum vendi potest.*\n(A thing is worth only what someone else will pay for it.)\nHOW THE RANDOM WALK IS TO BE CONDUCTED\nWith this introduction complete, join me on a random walk through the investment landscape, culminating in a stroll down Wall Street. My first task will be to familiarize you with historical pricing patterns and their relevance to the two theories of investment pricing. Santayana warned that those who do not learn from the past are doomed to repeat its errors. Therefore, I will describe some spectacular crazes from both the distant and recent past. Some readers may dismiss the public rush to buy tulip bulbs in seventeenth-century Netherlands and the eighteenth-century South Sea Bubble in England. However, no one can disregard the new-issue mania of the early 1960s, the Nifty Fifty craze of the 1970s, the incredible boom in Japanese land and stock prices followed by the equally dramatic crash in the early 1990s, the Internet craze of 1999 and early 2000, or the U.S. real estate bubble that ended in 2007. These events serve as continual reminders that neither individuals nor investment professionals are immune to the errors of the past.', 'English', '2025-08-04 06:39:47', '2025-08-04 06:39:47', '2025-08-04 03:39:47');
INSERT INTO `enhanced_texts` (`id`, `book_id`, `original_file`, `title`, `enhanced_text`, `target_language`, `processing_date`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(8, 11, '0005_THE_MADNESS_OF_CROWDS.txt', '**Title: The Recurring Specter of Speculative Frenzies**', '**Title: The Recurring Specter of Speculative Frenzies**\n**Text:**\nTHE MADNESS OF CROWDS\nOctober. This is one of the peculiarly dangerous months to speculate in stocks. The others are July, January, September, April, November, May, March, June, December, August, and February.\nMark Twain, Pudd\'nhead Wilson\nGREED RUN AMOK has been an essential feature of every spectacular boom in history. In their frenzy, market participants ignore firm foundations of value for the dubious but thrilling assumption that they can make a killing by building castles in the air. Such thinking has enveloped entire nations.\nThe psychology of speculation is a veritable theater of the absurd. Several of its plays are presented in this chapter. The castles that were built during the performances were based on Dutch tulip bulbs, English bubbles, and good old American blue-chip stocks. In each case, some of the people made money some of the time, but only a few emerged unscathed.\nHistory, in this instance, does teach a lesson: Although the castle-in-the-air theory can well explain such speculative binges, outguessing the reactions of a fickle crowd is a most dangerous game. In crowds, it is stupidity and not mother-wit that is accumulated, Gustave Le Bon noted in his 1895 classic on crowd psychology. It would appear that not many have read the book.\nSkyrocketing markets that depend on purely psychic support have invariably succumbed to the financial law of gravitation. Unsustainable prices may persist for years, but eventually they reverse themselves. Such reversals come with the suddenness of an earthquake; and the bigger the binge, the greater the resulting hangover. Few of the reckless builders of castles in the air have been nimble enough to anticipate these reversals and to escape when everything came tumbling down.\nTHE TULIP-BULB CRAZE\nThe tulip-bulb craze was one of the most spectacular get-rich-quick binges in history. Its excesses become even more vivid when one realizes that it happened in staid old Holland in the early seventeenth century. The events leading to this speculative frenzy were set in motion in 1593 when a newly appointed botany professor from Vienna brought to Leyden a collection of unusual plants that had originated in Turkey. The Dutch were fascinated with this new addition to the garden but not with the professor\'s asking price (he had hoped to sell the bulbs and make a handsome profit). One night a thief broke into the professor\'s house and stole the bulbs, which were subsequently sold at a lower price but at greater profit.\nOver the next decade or so, the tulip became a popular but expensive item in Dutch gardens. Many of these flowers succumbed to a nonfatal virus known as mosaic. It was this mosaic that helped to trigger the wild speculation in tulip bulbs. The virus caused the tulip petals to develop contrasting colored stripes or flames. The Dutch valued highly these infected bulbs, called bizarres. In a short time, popular taste dictated that the more bizarre a bulb, the greater the cost of owning it.\nSlowly, tulipmania set in. At first, bulb merchants simply tried to predict the most popular variegated style for the coming year, much as clothing manufacturers do in gauging the public\'s taste in fabric, color, and hemlines. Then they would buy an extra-large stockpile to anticipate a rise in price. Tulip-bulb prices began to rise wildly. The more expensive the bulbs became, the more people viewed them as smart investments. Charles Mackay, who chronicled these events in his book Extraordinary Popular Delusions and the Madness of Crowds, noted that the ordinary industry of the country was dropped in favor of speculation in tulip bulbs: Nobles, citizens, farmers, mechanics, seamen, footmen, maid-servants, even chimney sweeps and old clotheswomen dabbled in tulips. Everyone imagined that the passion for tulips would last forever.\nPeople who said the prices could not possibly go higher watched with chagrin as their friends and relatives made enormous profits. The temptation to join them was hard to resist. In the last years of the tulip spree, which lasted approximately from 1634 to early 1637, people started to barter their personal belongings, such as land, jewels, and furniture, to obtain the bulbs that would make them even wealthier. Bulb prices reached astronomical levels.\nPart of the genius of financial markets is that when there is a real demand for a method to enhance speculative opportunities, the market will surely provide it. The instruments that enabled tulip speculators to get the most action for their money were call options similar to those popular today in the stock market.\nA call option conferred on the holder the right to buy tulip bulbs (call for their delivery) at a fixed price (usually approximating the current market price) during a specified period. He was charged an amount called the option premium, which might run 15 to 20 percent of the current market price. An option on a tulip bulb currently worth 100 guilders, for example, would cost the buyer only about 20 guilders. If the price moved up to 200 guilders, the option holder would exercise his right; he would buy at 100 and simultaneously sell at the then-current price of 200. He then had a profit of 80 guilders (the 100 guilders appreciation less the 20 guilders he paid for the option). Thus, he enjoyed a fourfold increase in his money, whereas an outright purchase would only have doubled his money.\nOptions provide one way to leverage one\'s investment to increase the potential rewards as well as the risks. Such devices helped to ensure broad participation in the market. The same is true today.\nThe history of the period was filled with tragicomic episodes. One such incident concerned a returning sailor who brought news to a wealthy merchant of the arrival of a shipment of new goods. The merchant rewarded him with a breakfast of fine red herring. Seeing what he thought was an onion on the merchant\'s counter, and no doubt thinking it very much out of place amid silks and velvets, he proceeded to take it as a relish for his herring. Little did he dream that the onion would have fed a whole ship\'s crew for a year. It was a costly Semper Augustus tulip bulb. The sailor paid dearly for his relish—his no longer grateful host had him imprisoned for several months on a felony charge.\nHistorians regularly reinterpret the past, and some financial historians who have reexamined the evidence about various financial bubbles have argued that considerable rationality in pricing may have existed after all. One of these revisionist historians, Peter Garber, has suggested that tulip-bulb pricing in seventeenth-century Holland was far more rational than is commonly believed. Garber makes some good points, and I do not mean to imply that there was no rationality at all in the structure of bulb prices during the period. The Semper Augustus, for example, was a particularly rare and beautiful bulb and, as Garber reveals, was valued greatly even in the years before the tulipmania. Moreover, Garber\'s research indicates that rare individual bulbs commanded high prices even after the general collapse of bulb prices, albeit at levels that were only a fraction of their peak prices. But Garber can find no rational explanation for such phenomena as a twentyfold increase in tulip-bulb prices during January of 1637 followed by an even larger decline in prices in February. Apparently, as happens in all speculative crazes, prices eventually got so high that some people decided they would be prudent and sell their bulbs. Soon others followed suit. Like a snowball rolling downhill, bulb deflation grew at an increasingly rapid pace, and in no time at all panic reigned.\nGovernment ministers stated officially that there was no reason for tulip bulbs to fall in price, but no one listened. Dealers went bankrupt and refused to honor their commitments to buy tulip bulbs. A government plan to settle all contracts at 10 percent of their face value was frustrated when bulbs fell even below this mark. And prices continued to decline. Down and down they went until most bulbs became almost worthless, selling for no more than the price of a common onion.\nTHE SOUTH SEA BUBBLE\nSuppose your broker has called you and recommended that you invest in a new company with no sales or earnings—just great prospects. \"What business?\" you say. \"I\'m sorry,\" your broker explains, \"no one must know what the business is, but I can promise you enormous riches.\" A con game, you say. Right you are, but 300 years ago in England this was one of the hottest new issues of the period. And, just as you guessed, investors got very badly burned. The story illustrates how fraud can make greedy people even more eager to part with their money.\nAt the time of the South Sea Bubble, the British were ripe for throwing away money. A long period of prosperity had resulted in fat savings and thin investment outlets. In those days, owning stock was considered something of a privilege. As late as 1693, for example, only 499 souls benefited from ownership of East India stock. They reaped rewards in several ways, not least of which was that their dividends were untaxed. Also, their number included women, for stock represented one of the few forms of property that British women could possess in their own right. The South Sea Company, which obligingly filled the need for investment vehicles, had been formed in 1711 to restore faith in the government\'s ability to meet its obligations. The company took on a government IOU of almost 10 million. As a reward, it was given a monopoly over all trade to the South Seas. The public believed immense riches were to be made in such trade and regarded the stock with distinct favor.\nFrom the very beginning, the South Sea Company reaped profits at the expense of others. Holders of the government securities to be assumed by the company simply exchanged their securities for those of the South Sea Company. Those with prior knowledge of the plan quietly bought up government securities selling as low as 55 and then turned them in at par for 100 worth of South Sea stock when the company was incorporated. Not a single director of the company had the slightest experience in South American trade. This did not stop them from quickly outfitting African slave ships (the sale of slaves being one of the most lucrative features of South American trade). But even this venture did not prove profitable, because the mortality rate on the ships was so high.\nThe directors were, however, wise in the art of public appearance. An impressive house in London was rented, and the boardroom was furnished with thirty black Spanish upholstered chairs whose beechwood frames and gilt nails made them handsome to look at but uncomfortable to sit in. In the meantime, a shipload of company wool that was desperately needed in Vera Cruz was sent instead to Cartagena, where it rotted on the wharf for lack of buyers. Still, the stock of the company held its own and even rose modestly over the next few years despite the dilutive effect of bonus stock dividends and a war with Spain that led to a temporary collapse in trading opportunities. John Carswell, the author of an excellent history, The South Sea Bubble, wrote of John Blunt, a director and one of the prime promoters of the securities of the South Sea Company, that he continued to live his life with a prayer-book in his right hand and a prospectus in his left, never letting his right hand know what his left hand was doing.\nAcross the Channel, another company was formed by an exiled Englishman named John Law. Law\'s goal in life was to replace metal as money and create more liquidity through a national paper currency. (Bitcoin promotors are following a long tradition.) To further his purpose, Law acquired a derelict concern called the Mississippi Company and proceeded to build a conglomerate that became one of the largest capital enterprises ever to exist.\nThe Mississippi Company attracted speculators and their money from throughout the Continent. The word millionaire was invented at this time, and no wonder: The price of Mississippi stock rose from 100 to 2,000 in just two years, even though there was no logical reason for such an increase. At one time the inflated total market value of the stock of the Mississippi Company in France was more than eighty times that of all the gold and silver in the country.\nMeanwhile, back on the English side of the Channel, a bit of jingoism now began to appear in some of the great English houses. Why should all the money be going to the French Mississippi Company? What did England have to counter this? The answer was the South Sea Company, whose prospects were beginning to look a bit better, especially with the news that there would be peace with Spain and hence the way to the South American trade would at last be clear. Mexicans supposedly were waiting for the opportunity to empty their gold mines in return for England\'s abundant supply of cotton and woolen goods. This was free enterprise at its finest.\nIn 1720, the directors, an avaricious lot, decided to capitalize on their reputation by offering to fund the entire national debt, amounting to 31 million. This was boldness indeed, and the public loved it. When a bill to that effect was introduced in Parliament, the stock promptly rose from 130 to 300.\nVarious friends and backers who had shown interest in getting the bill passed were rewarded with free stock grants that could be sold back to the company when the price went up, with the individual collecting the profit. Among those rewarded were George I\'s mistress and her nieces, all of whom bore a startling resemblance to the king.\nOn April 12, 1720, five days after the bill became law, the South Sea Company sold a new issue of stock at 300. The issue could be bought on the installment plan—60 down and the rest in eight easy payments. Even the king could not resist; he subscribed for stock totaling 100,000. Fights broke out among other investors surging to buy. To ease the public appetite, the South Sea directors announced another new issue—this one at 400. But the public was ravenous. Within a month the stock was 550. On June 15 yet another issue was floated. This time the payment plan was even easier—10 percent down and not another payment for a year. The stock hit 800. Half the House of Lords and more than half the House of Commons signed on. Eventually, the price rose to 1,000. The speculative craze was in full bloom.\nNot even the South Sea Company was capable of handling the demands of all the fools who wanted to be parted from their money. Investors looked for other new ventures where they could get in on the ground floor. Just as speculators today search for the next Google, so in England in the early 1700s they looked for the next South Sea Company. Promoters obliged by organizing and bringing to the market a flood of new issues to meet the insatiable craving for investment.\nAs the days passed, new financing proposals ranged from ingenious to absurd—from importing a large number of jackasses from Spain (even though there was an abundant supply in England) to making salt water fresh. Increasingly the promotions involved some element of fraud, such as making boards out of sawdust. There were nearly one hundred different projects, each more extravagant and deceptive than the other, but each offering the hope of immense gain. They soon received the name of \"bubbles,\" as appropriate a name as could be devised. Like bubbles, they popped quickly—usually within a week or so.\nThe public, it seemed, would buy anything. New companies seeking financing during this period were organized for such purposes as the building of ships against pirates; encouraging the breeding of horses in England; trading in human hair; building hospitals for bastard children; extracting silver from lead; extracting sunlight from cucumbers; and even producing a wheel of perpetual motion.\nThe prize, however, must surely go to the unknown soul who started \"A Company for carrying on an undertaking of great advantage, but nobody to know what it is.\" The prospectus promised unheard-of rewards. At nine o\'clock in the morning, when the subscription books opened, crowds of people from all walks of life practically beat down the door in an effort to subscribe. Within five hours, one thousand investors handed over their money for shares in the company. Not being greedy himself, the promoter promptly closed up shop and set off for the Continent. He was never heard from again.\nNot all investors in the bubble companies believed in the feasibility of the schemes to which they subscribed. People were too sensible for that. They did believe, however, in the greater fool theory—that prices would rise, that buyers would be found, and that they would make money. Thus, most investors considered their actions the height of rationality, expecting that they could sell their shares at a premium in the after market, that is, the trading market in the shares after their initial issue.\nWhom the gods would destroy, they first ridicule. Signs that the end was near appeared with the issuance of a pack of South Sea playing cards. Each card contained a caricature of a bubble company, with an appropriate verse inscribed underneath. One of these, the Puckle Machine Company, was supposed to produce machines discharging both round and square cannonballs and bullets. Puckle claimed that his machine would revolutionize the art of war. The eight of spades, shown on the following page, described it as follows:\nA rare invention to destroy the crowd,\nOf fools at home instead of foes abroad:\nFear not my friends, this terrible machine,\nThey\'re only wounded that have shares therein.\nMany individual bubbles had been pricked without dampening the speculative enthusiasm, but the deluge came in August with an irreparable puncture to the South Sea Company. Realizing that the price of the shares in the market bore no relationship to the real prospects of the company, the directors and officers sold out in the summer.\nThe news leaked and the stock fell. Soon the price of the shares collapsed and panic reigned. The chart below shows the spectacular rise and fall of the stock of the South Sea Company. Government officials tried in vain to restore confidence, and a complete collapse of the public credit was barely averted. Similarly, the price of Mississippi Company shares fell to a pittance as the public realized that an excess of paper currency creates no real wealth, only inflation.\nBig losers in the South Sea Bubble included Isaac Newton, who exclaimed, \"I can calculate the motions of heavenly bodies, but not the madness of people.\" So much for castles in the air.\nTo protect the public from further abuses, Parliament passed the Bubble Act, which forbade the issuing of stock certificates by companies. For more than a century, until the act was repealed in 1825, there were relatively few share certificates in the British market.\nSource: Larry Neal, The Rise of Financial Capitalism (Cambridge University Press, 1990).\nWALL STREET LAYS AN EGG\nThe bulbs and bubbles are, admittedly, ancient history. Could the same sort of thing happen in more modern times? Let\'s turn to more recent events. America, the land of opportunity, had its turn in the 1920s. And given our emphasis on freedom and growth, we produced one of the most spectacular booms and loudest crashes civilization has ever known.\nConditions could not have been more favorable for a speculative craze. The country had been experiencing unrivaled prosperity. One could not but have faith in American business, and as Calvin Coolidge said, \"The business of America is business.\" Businessmen were likened to religious missionaries and almost deified. Such analogies were even made in the opposite direction. Bruce Barton, of the New York advertising agency Batten, Barton, Durstine & Osborn, wrote in The Man Nobody Knows that Jesus was the first businessman and that his parables were the most powerful advertisements of all time.\nIn 1928, stock-market speculation became a national pastime. From early March 1928 through early September 1929, the market\'s percentage increase equaled that of the entire period from 1923 through early 1928. Stock prices of major industrial corporations sometimes rose 10 or 15 points per day. The price increases are illustrated in the table below.\nAdjusted for stock splits and the value of rights received subsequent to March 3, 1928.\nNot everybody was speculating in the market. Borrowing to buy stocks (buying on margin) did increase from 1 billion in 1921 to almost 9 billion in 1929. Nevertheless, only about one million people owned stocks on margin in 1929. Still, the speculative spirit was at least as widespread as in the previous crazes and was certainly unrivaled in its intensity. More important, stock-market speculation was central to the culture. John Brooks, in Once in Golconda, recounted the remarks of a British correspondent newly arrived in New York: \"You could talk about Prohibition, or Hemingway, or air conditioning, or music, or horses, but in the end you had to talk about the stock market, and that was when the conversation became serious.\"\nUnfortunately, there were hundreds of smiling operators only too glad to help the public construct castles in the air. Manipulation on the stock exchange set new records for unscrupulousness. No better example can be found than the operation of investment pools. One such undertaking raised the price of RCA stock 61 points in four days.\nAn investment pool required close cooperation on the one hand and complete disdain for the public on the other. Generally such operations began when a number of traders banded together to manipulate a particular stock. They appointed a pool manager (who justifiably was considered something of an artist) and promised not to double-cross each other through private operations. The pool manager accumulated a large block of stock through inconspicuous buying over a period of weeks. If possible, he also obtained an option to buy a substantial block of stock at the current market price. Next he tried to enlist the stock\'s exchange specialist as an ally.\nPool members were in the swim with the specialist on their side. A stock-exchange specialist functions as a broker\'s broker. If a stock was trading at 50 a share and you gave your broker an order to buy at 45, the broker typically left that order with the specialist. If and when the stock fell to 45, the specialist then executed the order. All such orders to buy below the market price or sell above it were kept in the specialist\'s supposedly private book. Now you see why the specialist could be so valuable to the pool manager. The book gave information about the extent of existing orders to buy and sell at prices below and above the current market. It was always helpful to know as many of the cards of the public players as possible. Now the real fun was ready to begin.\nGenerally, at this point the pool manager had members of the pool trade among themselves. For example, Haskell sells 200 shares to Sidney at 40, and Sidney sells them back at 40⅛. The process is repeated with 400 shares at prices of 40¼ and 40½. Next comes the sale of a 1,000-share block at 40⅝, followed by another at 40¾. These sales were recorded on ticker tapes across the country, and the illusion of activity was conveyed to the thousands of tape watchers who crowded into the brokerage offices of the country. Such activity, generated by so-called wash sales, created the impression that something big was afoot.\nNow tipsheet writers and market commentators under the control of the pool manager would tell of exciting developments in the offing. The pool manager also tried to ensure that the flow of news from the company\'s management was increasingly favorable. If all went well, and in the speculative atmosphere of the 1928–29 period it could hardly miss, the combination of tape activity and managed news would bring the public in.\nOnce the public came in, the free-for-all started and it was time discreetly to pull the plug. As the public did the buying, the pool did the selling. The pool manager began feeding stock into the market, first slowly and then in larger and larger blocks before the public could collect its senses. At the end of the roller-coaster ride, the pool members had netted large profits and the public was left holding the suddenly deflated stock.\nBut people didn\'t have to band together to defraud the public. Many individuals, particularly corporate officers and directors, did quite well on their own. Take Albert Wiggin, the head of Chase, the nation\'s second-largest bank at the time. In July 1929, Mr. Wiggin became apprehensive about the dizzy heights to which stocks had climbed and no longer felt comfortable speculating on the bull side of the market. (He was rumored to have made millions in a pool boosting the price of his own bank.) Believing that the prospects for his own bank\'s stock were particularly dim, he sold short more than 42,000 shares of Chase stock. Selling short is a way to make money if stock prices fall. It involves selling stock you do not currently own in the expectation of buying it back later at a lower price. It\'s hoping to buy low and sell high, but in reverse order.\nWiggin\'s timing was perfect. Immediately after the short sale, the price of Chase stock began to fall, and when the crash came in the fall the stock dropped precipitously. When the account was closed in November, he had netted a multimillion-dollar profit from the operation. Conflicts of interest apparently did not trouble Mr. Wiggin. In fairness, it should be pointed out that he did retain a net ownership position in Chase stock during this period. Nevertheless, the rules in existence today would not allow an insider to make short-swing profits from trading his own stock.\nOn September 3, 1929, the market averages reached a peak that was not to be surpassed for a quarter of a century. The endless chain of prosperity was soon to break; general business activity had already turned down months before. Prices drifted for the next day, and on the following day, September 5, the market suffered a sharp decline known as the \"Babson Break.\"\nThis was named in honor of Roger Babson, a frail, goateed, pixyish-looking financial adviser from Wellesley, Massachusetts. At a financial luncheon that day, he had said, \"I repeat what I said at this time last year and the year before, that sooner or later a crash is coming.\" Wall Street professionals greeted the new pronouncements from the \"sage of Wellesley,\" as he was known, with their usual derision.\nAs Babson implied, he had been predicting the crash for several years and he had yet to be proven right. Nevertheless, at two o\'clock in the afternoon, when Babson\'s words were quoted on the broad tape (the Dow Jones financial news tape, which was an essential part of the furniture in every brokerage house), the market went into a nosedive. In the last frantic hour of trading, American Telephone and Telegraph went down 6 points, Westinghouse 7 points, and U.S. Steel 9 points. It was a prophetic episode. After the Babson Break the possibility of a crash, which was entirely unthinkable a month before, suddenly became a common subject for discussion.\nConfidence faltered. September had many more bad than good days. At times the market fell sharply. Bankers and government officials assured the country that there was no cause for concern. Professor Irving Fisher of Yale, one of the progenitors of the intrinsic-value theory, offered his soon-to-be-immortal opinion that \"stocks had reached what looked like a permanently high plateau.\"\nBy Monday, October 21, the stage was set for a classic stock-market break. The declines in stock prices had led to calls for more collateral from margin customers. Unable or unwilling to meet the calls, these customers were forced to sell their holdings. This depressed prices and led to more margin calls and finally to a self-sustaining selling wave.\nThe volume of sales on October 21 zoomed to more than 6 million shares. The ticker fell way behind, to the dismay of the tens of thousands of individuals watching the tape from brokerage houses around the country. Nearly an hour and forty minutes had elapsed after the close of the market before the last transaction was actually recorded on the stock ticker.\nThe indomitable Fisher dismissed the decline as \"a shaking out of the lunatic fringe that attempts to speculate on margin.\" He went on to say that prices of stocks during the boom had not caught up with their real value and would go higher. Among other things, the professor believed that the market had not yet reflected the beneficent effects of Prohibition, which had made the American worker more productive and dependable.\nOn October 24, later called Black Thursday, the market volume reached almost 13 million shares. Prices sometimes fell 5 and 10 on each trade. Many issues dropped 40 and 50 points during a couple of hours. On the next day, Herbert Hoover offered his famous diagnosis, \"The fundamental business of the country . . . is on a sound and prosperous basis.\"\nTuesday, October 29, 1929, was among the most catastrophic days in the history of the New York Stock Exchange. Only October 19 and 20, 1987, rivaled in intensity the panic on the exchange. More than 16.4 million shares were traded on that day in 1929. (A 16-million-share day in 1929 would be equivalent to a multibillion-share day in 2014 because of the greater number of listed shares.) Prices fell almost perpendicularly, and kept on falling, as is illustrated by the following table, which shows the extent of the decline during the autumn of 1929 and over the next three years. With the exception of safe AT&T, which lost only three-quarters of its value, most blue-chip stocks had fallen 95 percent or more by the time the lows were reached in 1932.\nAdjusted for stock splits and the value of rights received subsequent to September 3, 1929.\nPerhaps the best summary of the debacle was given by Variety, the show-business weekly, which headlined the story \"Wall Street Lays an Egg.\" The speculative boom was dead, and billions of dollars of share values as well as the dreams of millions were wiped out. The crash in the stock market was followed by the most devastating depression in history.\nAgain, there are revisionist historians who say there was a method to the madness of the stock-market boom of the late 1920s. Harold Bierman Jr., for example, in his book The Great Myths of 1929, has suggested that, without perfect foresight, stocks were not obviously overpriced in 1929. After all, very intelligent people, such as Irving Fisher and John Maynard Keynes, believed that stocks were reasonably priced. Bierman goes on to argue that the extreme optimism undergirding the stock market might even have been justified had it not been for inappropriate monetary policies. The crash itself, in his view, was precipitated by the Federal Reserve Board\'s policy of raising interest rates to punish speculators. There are at least grains of truth in Bierman\'s arguments, and economists today often blame the severity of the 1930s depression on the Federal Reserve for allowing the money supply to decline sharply. Nevertheless, history teaches us that very sharp increases in stock prices are seldom followed by a gradual return to relative price stability. Even if prosperity had continued into the 1930s, stock prices could never have sustained their advance of the late 1920s.\nIn addition, the anomalous behavior of closed-end investment company shares (which I will cover in chapter 15) provides clinching evidence of wide-scale stock-market irrationality during the 1920s. The fundamental value of these closed-end funds consists of the market value of the securities they hold. In most periods since 1930, these funds have sold at discounts of 10 to 20 percent from their asset values. From January to August 1929, however, the typical closed-end fund sold at a premium of 50 percent. Moreover, the premiums for some of the best-known funds were astronomical. Goldman, Sachs Trading Corporation sold at twice its net asset value. Tri-Continental Corporation sold at 256 percent of its asset value. This meant that you could go to your broker and buy, say, AT&T at whatever its market price was, or you would purchase it through the fund at 2½ times the market value. It was irrational speculative enthusiasm that drove the prices of these funds far above the value at which their individual security holdings could be purchased.\nAN AFTERWORD\nWhy are memories so short? Why do such speculative crazes seem so isolated from the lessons of history? I have no apt answer, but I am convinced that Bernard Baruch was correct in suggesting that a study of these events can help equip investors for survival. The consistent losers in the market, from my personal experience, are those who are unable to resist being swept up in some kind of tulip-bulb craze. It is not hard to make money in the market. What is hard to avoid is the alluring temptation to throw your money away on short, get-rich-quick speculative binges. It is an obvious lesson, but one frequently ignored.\nGolconda, now in ruins, was a city in India. According to legend, everyone who passed through it became rich.', 'English', '2025-08-04 06:40:26', '2025-08-04 06:40:26', '2025-08-04 03:40:26');
INSERT INTO `enhanced_texts` (`id`, `book_id`, `original_file`, `title`, `enhanced_text`, `target_language`, `processing_date`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(9, 11, '0006_SPECULATIVE_BUBBLES_FROM_THE_SIXTIES_INTO_THE.txt', '**Title: Speculative Bubbles: From the Sixties to the Nineties**', '**Title: Speculative Bubbles: From the Sixties to the Nineties**\n**Text:**\n\"Everything\'s got a moral if only you can find it.\" - Lewis Carroll, *Alice\'s Adventures in Wonderland*\nThe madness of crowds can be truly spectacular. Examples such as these have persuaded many to entrust their money to professional portfolio managers, overseeing large pension and retirement funds, mutual funds, and investment counseling organizations. While the crowd may be irrational, institutions are perceived as above such behavior. Let\'s examine the rationality of these institutions.\n**The Sanity of Institutions**\nBy the 1990s, institutions accounted for over 90% of the trading volume on the New York Stock Exchange. One might expect that the hardheaded, meticulous reasoning of professionals would prevent the extravagant excesses of the past. Yet, professional investors participated in several distinct speculative movements from the 1960s through the 1990s. In each case, institutions actively bid for stocks, not because they believed the stocks were undervalued based on fundamental principles, but because they anticipated that even greater fools would buy the shares at inflated prices. Given the relevance of these speculative movements to today\'s markets, this institutional overview should be particularly useful.\n**The Soaring Sixties**\n*The New New Era: The Growth-Stock New-Issue Craze*\nMy Wall Street career began in 1959, and \"growth\" was the magic word, imbued with almost mystical significance. Growth companies like IBM and Texas Instruments traded at price-earnings multiples exceeding 80. (A year later, these multiples were in the 20s and 30s.)\nQuestioning these valuations was considered heresy. While these prices couldn\'t be justified by fundamental principles, investors believed that buyers would eagerly pay even higher prices. Lord Keynes must have smiled quietly from wherever economists go after death. I remember a senior partner at my firm shaking his head and admitting that no one who remembered the 1929-32 crash would buy and hold these high-priced growth stocks. But the \"young Turks\" prevailed. Newsweek quoted a broker saying, \"Speculators think anything they buy will double overnight. The horrible thing is, it has happened.\"\nMore was to come. Promoters, eager to satisfy the insatiable investor appetite for space-age stocks during the Soaring Sixties, created more new issues in the 1959-62 period than ever before. This new-issue mania rivaled the South Sea Bubble in intensity and, regrettably, in fraudulent practices.\nIt was called the \"tronics boom\" because stock offerings often included a garbled version of \"electronics\" in their title, even if the companies had nothing to do with the industry. Buyers didn\'t care what the companies made, as long as it sounded electronic and suggested something esoteric. For example, American Music Guild, which sold phonograph records and players door-to-door, changed its name to Space-Tone before going public. The shares were sold at $2 and rose to $14 within weeks.\nJack Dreyfus, of Dreyfus and Company, commented on the mania: \"Take a nice little company that\'s been making shoelaces for 40 years and sells at a respectable six times earnings ratio. Change the name from Shoelaces, Inc. to Electronics and Silicon Furth-Burners. In today\'s market, the words \'electronics\' and \'silicon\' are worth 15 times earnings. However, the real play comes from the word \'furth-burners,\' which no one understands. A word that no one understands entitles you to double your entire score. Therefore, we have six times earnings for the shoelace business and 15 times earnings for electronic and silicon, or a total of 21 times earnings. Multiply this by two for furth-burners, and we now have a score of 42 times earnings for the new company.\"\nThe numbers tell the story. Even Mother\'s Cookie could have achieved a sizable gain. Imagine the glory if it had been called Mothertron\'s Cookitronics! Ten years later, most of these companies were nearly worthless, and today, none exist.\nWhere was the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC)? Aren\'t new issuers required to register with the SEC? Can\'t they (and their underwriters) be punished for false and misleading statements? The SEC was present, but by law, it had to remain passive. As long as a company prepared and distributed an adequate prospectus, the SEC couldn\'t save buyers from themselves. Many prospectuses contained warnings in bold letters on the cover:\n**WARNING: THIS COMPANY HAS NO ASSETS OR EARNINGS AND WILL BE UNABLE TO PAY DIVIDENDS IN THE FORESEEABLE FUTURE. THE SHARES ARE HIGHLY RISKY.**\nJust as warnings on cigarette packs don\'t stop people from smoking, warnings about investment dangers don\'t prevent speculators from handing over their money. The SEC can warn fools, but it can\'t prevent them from parting with their money. Buyers were so convinced the stocks would rise that the underwriter\'s problem wasn\'t selling the shares, but allocating them among frenzied purchasers.\nFraud and market manipulation are different matters. Here, the SEC can and has taken strong action. Many little-known brokerage houses on the fringes of respectability, responsible for most new issues and their price manipulation, were suspended for various peculations.\nThe tronics boom ended in 1962. Yesterday\'s hot issue became today\'s \"cold turkey.\" Many professionals refused to admit they had speculated recklessly. Few acknowledged that hindsight makes it easy to identify overvalued or undervalued prices. Even fewer admitted that nobody truly knows the proper price of a stock at any given time.\n*Synergy Generates Energy: The Conglomerate Boom*\nThe financial market\'s genius lies in its ability to produce any demanded product. Investors desired expected growth in earnings per share. If growth couldn\'t be found organically, someone would find another way to create it. By the mid-1960s, creative entrepreneurs suggested that growth could be created through \"synergism.\"\nSynergism is the idea that 2 + 2 = 5. Two separate companies with $2 million in earnings each might produce combined earnings of $5 million if consolidated. This magical creation was called a \"conglomerate.\"\nAntitrust laws prevented large companies from purchasing firms in the same industry, but buying firms in other industries was permissible. Consolidations were carried out in the name of synergism, ostensibly to achieve higher sales and earnings than the independent entities could. However, the primary impetus for the conglomerate wave was that the acquisition process itself could generate growth in earnings per share. Conglomerate managers tended to possess financial expertise rather than the operational skills needed to improve the profitability of acquired companies. Through financial legerdemain, they could assemble a group of companies with no basic potential and produce steadily rising per-share earnings. The following example illustrates this manipulation:\nConsider Able Circuit Smasher Company (an electronics firm) and Baker Candy Company (which makes chocolate bars). Each has 200,000 shares outstanding. In 1965, both companies earn $1 million a year, or $5 per share. Assume neither business is growing and earnings will remain constant.\nThe two firms sell at different prices. Able Circuit Smasher Company, in the electronics business, has a price-earnings multiple of 20, giving it a market price of $100 (20 x $5). Baker Candy Company, in a less glamorous business, has a multiple of only 10, resulting in a market price of $50 (10 x $5).\nAble Circuit\'s management wants to become a conglomerate. It offers to absorb Baker by swapping stock at a rate of two Able shares for every three Baker shares. Baker shareholders receive $200 worth of Able stock for every $150 worth of Baker stock, which they are likely to accept.\nThe budding conglomerate, now named Synergon, Inc., has 333,333 shares outstanding and total earnings of $2 million, or $6 per share. By 1966, earnings have risen by 20%, from $5 to $6, justifying Able\'s former price-earnings multiple of 20. Consequently, Synergon (formerly Able) rises from $100 to $120, enriching everyone. Baker shareholders also avoid taxes on their profits until they sell their Synergon shares.\nA year later, Synergon finds Charlie Company, which earns $10 per share, or $1 million with 100,000 shares outstanding. Charlie Company is in the risky military-hardware business, so its shares have a multiple of only 10 and sell at $100. Synergon offers a share-for-share exchange. Charlie\'s shareholders are delighted to exchange their $100 shares for Synergon\'s $120 shares. By the end of 1967, the combined company has $3 million in earnings, 433,333 shares outstanding, and $6.92 earnings per share.\nHere, the conglomerate has literally manufactured growth. None of the three companies was growing, but their merger created the illusion of growth. Synergon is a growth stock, and its performance justifies a high, possibly increasing, earnings multiple.\nThe trick is the electronics company swapping its high-multiple stock for a lower-multiple stock. The candy company\'s earnings sell at a multiple of 10, but when averaged with the electronics company\'s earnings, the total earnings (including chocolate bar sales) sell at a multiple of 20. The more acquisitions Synergon makes, the faster earnings per share grow, making the stock more attractive and justifying its high multiple.\nThe whole scheme is a chain letter: no one gets hurt as long as acquisitions grow exponentially. While unsustainable, the possibilities were mind-boggling for early participants. It seems unbelievable that Wall Street professionals fell for this con game, but they did for several years. Or, subscribing to the castle-in-the-air theory, they believed others would fall for it.\nAutomatic Sprinkler Corporation (later A-T-O, Inc., then Figgie International, at the urging of CEO Mr. Figgie) exemplifies this game. Between 1963 and 1968, sales rose over 1,400%, solely through acquisitions. In mid-1967, four mergers were completed in twenty-five days. These acquisitions, at low price-earnings multiples, sharply increased earnings per share. The market responded by bidding up the price-earnings multiple to over 50 in 1967 and the stock price from $8 in 1963 to $73.625 in 1967.\nMr. Figgie performed the public relations necessary to build Wall Street\'s castle in the air, sprinkling his conversations with buzzwords about the energy of the free-form company and its interface with change and technology. He emphasized that he reviewed twenty to thirty deals for each one he bought. Wall Street loved it.\nMr. Figgie wasn\'t alone. Conglomerate managers invented a new language to dazzle the investment community, discussing market matrices, core technology fulcrums, modular building blocks, and the nucleus theory of growth. Wall Street didn\'t understand the words but felt good about being in the technological mainstream.\nConglomerate managers also redefined their businesses. Shipbuilding became marine systems, zinc mining became the space minerals division, and steel fabrication plants became the materials technology division. A lighting fixture or lock company became part of the protective services division. If a security analyst dared to ask how a foundry or meat packer could achieve 15-20% growth, they were told about efficiency experts isolating millions in excess costs, marketing research finding fresh markets, and profit margins tripling within two years. Instead of declining with merger activity, conglomerate stock multiples rose for a while.\nThe music stopped on January 19, 1968, when Litton Industries, the granddaddy of conglomerates, announced that second-quarter earnings would be substantially lower than forecast. After nearly a decade of 20% yearly increases, the market, believing in alchemy, reacted with disbelief and shock. Conglomerate stocks declined roughly 40% before a feeble recovery.\nWorse followed. In July, the Federal Trade Commission announced an in-depth investigation of the conglomerate merger movement, causing further stock declines. The SEC and the accounting profession began clarifying reporting techniques for mergers and acquisitions. Sell orders flooded in. The SEC and the Assistant Attorney General expressed strong concerns about the accelerating merger pace.\nThe aftermath revealed two disturbing factors. First, conglomerates couldn\'t always control their empires. Investors became disenchanted with the \"new math\"; 2 + 2 didn\'t equal 5, and some doubted it even equaled 4. Second, government and accounting concerns about the pace and potential abuses of mergers reduced, and often eliminated, the premium multiples paid for earnings growth from acquisitions. This made the alchemy game almost impossible, as the acquiring company needed a larger earnings multiple than the acquired company for the ploy to work.\nAn interesting footnote is that deconglomeration became fashionable in the 2000s. Spinning off subsidiaries into separate companies generally resulted in rising stock prices, with the combined market value of the two distinct companies often exceeding the original conglomerate\'s value.\n*Performance Comes to the Market: The Bubble in Concept Stocks*\nWith conglomerates failing, investment fund managers found a new magic word: performance. Selling a mutual fund with stocks that increased in value faster than competitors\' portfolios became the goal.\nSome funds did perform, at least briefly. Fred Carr\'s Enterprise Fund achieved a 117% total return (including dividends and capital gains) in 1967, followed by 44% in 1968. The Standard & Poor\'s 500-Stock Index returned 25% and 11% respectively. This performance attracted new money. The public bet on the jockey rather than the horse.\nHow did they do it? They concentrated portfolios in dynamic stocks with compelling stories, quickly switching to even better stories. This strategy worked initially and attracted imitators. These \"go-go funds\" and their \"youthful gunslinger\" managers attracted investment dollars into the riskiest performance funds.\nPerformance investing took hold in the late 1960s. Because near-term performance was crucial (investment services published monthly mutual-fund performance records), buying stocks with exciting concepts and believable stories that the market would recognize soon was best. Thus, the \"concept stock\" was born.\nEven if the story wasn\'t entirely believable, as long as the manager believed the average opinion would believe the story, it sufficed. Martin Mayer quoted a fund manager saying, \"Since we hear stories early, we can figure enough people will be hearing it in the next few days to give the stock a bounce, even if the story doesn\'t prove out.\" Many saw this as a radical new investment strategy, but John Maynard Keynes had identified it in 1936.\nEnter Cortes W. Randell. His concept was a youth company for the youth market. He founded, presided over, and was the major stockholder of National Student Marketing (NSM). He sold an image of affluence and success, owning a white Learjet named Snoopy, an apartment in New York\'s Waldorf Towers, a castle with a mock dungeon in Virginia, and a yacht that slept twelve. He displayed expensive golf clubs by his office door, used only at night by the cleaning crew to drive wads of paper along the carpet.\nRandell spent his time visiting institutional fund managers or calling from his Lear, selling NSM like a South Sea Bubble promoter. His real talent was evangelism. Wall Street bought the concept of a single company serving the needs of young people. NSM grew through mergers, like the ordinary conglomerates. The difference was that each company related to the college-age youth market, from posters and records to sweatshirts and summer job directories. What was more appealing to a youthful gunslinger than a youth-oriented concept stock? Glowing press releases and increasingly optimistic earnings projections followed.\nInstitutional investors are clearly as adept as the public at building castles in the air.\nMinnie Pearl, a fast-food franchising firm, was especially accommodating. To please the financial community, Minnie Pearl\'s chickens became Performance Systems. What better name for performance-oriented investors? On Wall Street, a rose by any other name does not smell as sweet. The price-earnings multiple indicates infinity, as Performance Systems had no earnings when it reached its high in 1968. Both companies \"laid an egg.\"\nWhy did the stocks perform so poorly? Their price-earnings multiples were inflated beyond reason. Dropping from 100 to 20 loses 80% of the investment. Most concept companies faced operating difficulties: rapid expansion, excessive debt, loss of management control, etc. They were run by promoters, not operators. Fraudulent practices were common; Cortes Randell pleaded guilty to accounting fraud and served eight months in prison.\n**The Nifty Fifty**\nIn the 1970s, Wall Street pros vowed to return to sound principles. Concepts were out, and blue-chip companies were in. They wouldn\'t crash like the speculative favorites of the 1960s. Buying their shares and relaxing on the golf course was the prudent course.\nThere were only four dozen or so of these premier growth stocks: IBM, Xerox, Avon Products, Kodak, McDonald\'s, Polaroid, and Disney, known as the Nifty Fifty. They were large-capitalization stocks, allowing institutions to buy significant positions without market disruption. Because timing the market is difficult, these stocks seemed sensible. A temporarily high price didn\'t matter, as these proven growers would eventually justify it. These were \"one-decision stocks,\" bought once and never sold.\nThese stocks were also respectable. Colleagues wouldn\'t question investing in IBM. Losing money on IBM wasn\'t considered imprudent (unlike losing money on Performance Systems or National Student Marketing). Like greyhounds chasing the mechanical rabbit, pension funds, insurance companies, and bank trust funds loaded up on the Nifty Fifty one-decision growth stocks. Institutions began speculating in blue chips, ignoring that no company could grow fast enough to justify an earnings multiple of 80 or 90. They proved that well-packaged stupidity can sound like wisdom.\n*The Demise of the Nifty Fifty*\nThe Nifty Fifty craze ended like all speculative manias. The same managers who worshipped the Nifty Fifty decided they were overpriced and sold. The premier growth stocks fell completely from favor.\n**The Roaring Eighties**\n*The Return of New Issues*\nThe high-technology, new-issue boom of the first half of 1983 mirrored the 1960s episodes, with names altered to include biotechnology and microelectronics. The 1983 craze dwarfed the promoters of the 1960s. The total value of new issues in 1983 exceeded the cumulative total for the preceding decade. Initial public offerings (IPOs) were the hottest game.\nConsider Androbot, a company planning to mass-produce personal robots, and Stuff Your Face, Inc., a chain of three restaurants in New Jersey. Even Fine Art Acquisitions Ltd., an aesthetic enterprise acquiring and distributing fine prints and Art Deco sculpture replicas, participated. One major asset was nude photographs of Brooke Shields, taken between her time in the stroller and her entrance to Princeton, originally owned by Garry Gross. While Fine Arts saw no issue with the pictures of the eleven-year-old, her mother did. The pictures were returned to Gross and never sold. Fine Arts morphed into Dyansen Corporation, with a gallery in Trump Tower, and eventually defaulted in 1993 on a loan from Chrysler Credit Corporation.\nMuhammad Ali Arcades International\'s offering likely burst the bubble. It offered units of one share and two warrants for $1, 333 times what insiders paid. When it was discovered that Ali hadn\'t bought stock in his namesake company, investors reconsidered, leading to a dramatic decline in small-company stocks and IPOs. Many investors lost up to 90% of their money within a year.\nMuhammad Ali Arcades International\'s prospectus featured a picture of Ali standing over a fallen opponent. Ali claimed he could \"float like a butterfly and sting like a bee.\" The Ali Arcades offering (and Androbot\'s) never floated, but many others did, particularly technology stocks. Investors were stung.\n*Concepts Conquer Again: The Biotechnology Bubble*\nBiotechnology became the 1980s\' equivalent of the 1960s\' electronics. The biotech revolution was likened to the computer revolution, and optimism about gene-splicing was reflected in biotech stock prices.\nGenentech came to market in 1980. The stock tripled in value within twenty minutes of trading. Other biotech new issues were eagerly bought by investors seeking to enter a multibillion-dollar industry on the ground floor. Interferon, a cancer-fighting drug, drove the first wave. Analysts predicted $1 billion in sales by 1982 (actual sales were barely $200 million in 1989). Analysts continually predicted an earnings explosion in two years, but were disappointed. The technological revolution was real, and even weak companies benefited.\nBiotechnology stock valuations reached unprecedented levels. In the 1960s, speculative growth stocks sold at 50 times earnings. In the 1980s, some biotech stocks sold at 50 times sales. As a valuation student, I was fascinated by how analysts rationalized these prices. Because biotech companies had no current earnings (and no expected positive earnings for years) and little sales, new valuation methods were devised. My favorite was the \"product asset valuation method,\" estimating the value of all products in the pipeline. Even if the product was just genetic engineer drawings, potential sales volume and profit margin were estimated. The total value of the product pipeline determined the stock\'s fair price.\nWould FDA approval be delayed? (Interferon was delayed for years.) Would the market bear the projected drug prices? Would patent protection be possible, given simultaneous development by several companies? Would the marketing partner siphon off potential profit? In the mid-1980s, these problems seemed unreal. Biotech stocks were considered less risky than standard drug companies because they had no old products with declining revenues. Having positive sales and earnings was a drawback. But in the late 1980s, most biotechnology stocks lost three-quarters of their market value. Even real technology revolutions don\'t guarantee investor benefits.\n*ZZZZ Best Bubble of All*\nThe ZZZZ Best saga is an incredible Horatio Alger story. Barry Minkow was a 1980s legend. His career began at age nine, working at his mother\'s carpet-cleaning shop. By ten, he was cleaning carpets. Working evenings and summers, he saved $6,000 and, at fifteen, started his own carpet-cleaning business in the family garage, called ZZZZ Best. Still in high school, Minkow hired a crew while he fretted over payroll. The business flourished. He hired his parents. By eighteen, Minkow was a millionaire.\nMinkow promoted himself. He drove a red Ferrari, lived in a lavish home with a pool featuring a black Z, and wrote a book, *Making It in America*, claiming teenagers didn\'t work hard enough. He appeared on Oprah and recorded antidrug commercials with the slogan \"My act is clean, how\'s yours?\" ZZZZ Best had 1,300 employees and locations throughout California, Arizona, and Nevada.\nWas 100 times earnings too much for a carpet-cleaning company? Not when run by a successful businessman who could show toughness. Minkow\'s favorite line was \"My way or the highway.\" He boasted that he would fire his mother if she stepped out of line. When Minkow told Wall Street that his company was better run than IBM and would become the General Motors of carpet cleaning, investors listened raptly. One analyst said, \"This one can\'t miss.\"\nIn 1987, Minkow\'s bubble burst. ZZZZ Best was laundering money for the mob, acting as a front for organized crime figures who bought equipment with dirty money and replaced their investment with cash skimmed from the legitimate carpet-cleaning business. The growth was produced with fictitious contracts and phony credit card charges. The operation was a Ponzi scheme. Minkow was also charged with skimming millions for personal use.\nIn 1989, Minkow, then twenty-three, was convicted of fifty-seven counts of fraud, sentenced to twenty-five years in prison, and required to make $26 million restitution. The judge said, \"You are dangerous because you have this gift of gab, this ability to communicate. You don\'t have a conscience.\"\nMinkow spent fifty-four months in prison, became a born-again Christian, and earned degrees from Liberty University. After his release in 1994, he became senior pastor at Community Bible Church in California, wrote books, and was hired as an FBI adviser on fraud. In 2006, his prosecutor wrote, \"Barry has made a remarkable turnaround...uncovering more fraud than he ever perpetrated.\" In 2010, the movie *Minkow* was released, billed as a tale of redemption.\nUnfortunately, the movie was fiction. In 2011, Minkow was sentenced to five years in prison for securities fraud; in 2014, he pleaded guilty to embezzling $3 million from his church. Minkow never reformed.\n**What Does It All Mean?**\nMarket history is clear. Styles and fashions in security evaluations play a critical role in pricing. The stock market conforms to the castle-in-the-air theory, making investing dangerous.\nInvestors should be wary of new issues. Most IPOs underperform the market. Buying after trading begins, usually at a higher price, increases the likelihood of loss. Treat new issues with skepticism.\nInvestors have built many castles in the air with IPOs. The major sellers are the company managers, timing sales to coincide with peaks in prosperity or investor enthusiasm. The urge to get on the bandwagon produced a profitless prosperity for investors.\n*The Japanese Yen for Land and Stocks*\nI\'ve covered only U.S. speculative bubbles. One of the largest booms and busts involved the Japanese real estate and stock markets. From 1955 to 1990, Japanese real estate value increased over 75 times. By 1990, Japanese property was valued at nearly $20 trillion, over 20% of the world\'s wealth and double the world\'s stock markets. America is twenty-five times larger than Japan, yet Japan\'s property in 1990 was worth five times more than all American property.\nTheoretically, the Japanese could have bought all American property by selling metropolitan Tokyo. Selling the Imperial Palace would have bought all of California.\nThe stock market rose similarly. Stock prices increased 100-fold from 1955 to 1990. In December 1989, Japanese stocks were valued at $4 trillion, almost 1.5 times the value of U.S. equities and close to 45% of the world\'s equity-market capitalization. Firm-foundation investors were aghast. Japanese stocks sold at over 60 times earnings, almost 5 times book value, and over 200 times dividends. U.S. stocks sold at about 15 times earnings, and London equities sold at 12 times earnings. NTT Corporation, Japan\'s telephone giant, exceeded the value of AT&T, IBM, Exxon, General Electric, and General Motors combined.\nMarket supporters had answers. Price-earnings ratios were high because Japanese earnings were understated due to overstated depreciation charges and the exclusion of affiliated firm earnings. Adjusted multiples would be lower. Yields were low because of low interest rates. Stock prices were five times the value of assets because book values didn\'t reflect land appreciation. High land value was explained by population density and land-use regulations.\nHowever, these explanations were flawed. Even adjusted multiples were higher than in other countries and inflated relative to Japan\'s history. Japanese profitability was declining, and the strong yen made exporting difficult. While land was scarce, Japanese manufacturers found abundant land for new plants abroad. Rental income rose slower than land values, indicating a falling return on real estate. Low interest rates were already rising in 1989.\nIn 1990, Isaac Newton arrived in Japan. The Bank of Japan saw inflation stirring amid borrowing and liquidity, restricted credit, and raised interest rates, hoping to choke off property price rises and ease the stock market downward.\nThe stock market collapsed, almost as severely as the U.S. crash from 1929 to 1932. The Nikkei reached almost 40,000 on the last trading day of the 1980s. By mid-August 1992, it had declined to 14,309, a drop of about 63%. The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell 66% from December 1929 to its low in the summer of 1932. The rise in stock prices during the mid- and late 1980s represented a change in valuation relationships. The fall from 1990 reflected a return to the price-to-book-value relationships typical in the early 1980s.\nThe real estate bubble also burst in the early 1990s, with a decline roughly as severe as the stock market. The bursting of the bubble destroyed the myth that Japan was different and that its asset prices would always rise. The financial laws of gravity know no geographic boundaries.', 'English', '2025-08-04 06:41:17', '2025-08-04 06:41:17', '2025-08-04 03:41:17');
